\section{General Properties of SiC}

SiC is a semiconductor material having suitable properties for high power, high frequency and high temperature applications. SiC is a wide bandgap semiconductor material with high breakdown electric field strength, high saturated drift velocity of electrons, robust structure, and a high thermal conductivity as compared to many other semiconductors as explained in the Table \ref{Table 1.2} \cite{Elasser2002,Dreike1994}. In this table, $E_{g}$ is bandgap, $\varepsilon_{s}$ represents relative permittivity, $\mu$ is the electron mobility, $\upsilon_s$ represents saturation velocity, $E_{crit}$ is the critical electric field at which breakdown takes place and $\kappa$ represents thermal conductivity. Additionally, SiC is a hard substance with a Young's modulus of 394 GPa \cite{Tong1992}. It is chemically inert and reacts poorly with any known material at room temperature.

