\hline
\end{tabular}
\label{Table 1.2}
\end{center}
\end{table}

The most commonly used poly type of SiC is 4H-SiC, which has a bandgap of 3.265 eV. The wide bandgap made SiC an attractive choice for high temperature electronics fabrication. The breakdown field of SiC is six times higher than Si, making it a natural choice for high power electronics. Therefore, devices fabricated using SiC can operate at much higher voltages and temperatures compared to Si and GaAs.

Drift velocity plays a significant role in the operation of a device especially, when the device is meant for high frequency applications. In SiC, the saturation drift velocity, $\upsilon_s=2.2\times10^{7}$ cm/sec, which is twice that of Si. A high value of $\upsilon_s$ allows faster communication between the two electrodes needed for microwave applications. Further, an increase in temperature, generally, changes electrical properties of a device, like, mobility of free carriers, $\mu$, drift velocity, $\upsilon$, etc., which normally affects the device in a negative way. SiC is a thermally stable material relative to its counterparts, therefore, variation in its electrical properties is relatively low. This can be judged by comparing thermal conductivity of SiC with known conductors. For example, thermal conductivity of copper and silver is 4 W/(cm-K) and 4.18 W/(cm-K), respectively \cite{Saddow2004}; whereas, the value of thermal conductivity for SiC is 5 W/(cm-K) as reported in \cite{Slack1964}. A relatively high value of thermal conductivity indicates that SiC devices will allow heat to dissipate quickly thus, keeping intact the electrical performance of the device. Assuming that lattice temperature of a semiconductor is represented by $T$, its value depends on the maximum power dissipation, $P_{MD}$ and thermal resistance, $R_{th}$ as given below
\begin{equation}
\label{Eq:1.1}
\textit{T}=P_{MD}\times{\textit{R}_{th}}~.
\end{equation}
Since, $R_{th}$ of SiC is smaller than its counter parts therefore, under high power operating conditions, low lattice heating is observed. Thus, devices fabricated from SiC require simple, smaller and lighter cooling systems.

Another important factor, which is commonly used to assess the performance of a device is its free carriers mobility. In SiC, electron low field mobility, $\mu_{0}$ is described as \cite{Caughey1967}:
\begin{equation}
\label{Eq:1.2}
\mu_{0}(N_d)=\mu_{min}+\dfrac{\mu_{max}-\mu_{min}}{1+\left(N_d/N_{r} \right)^{\alpha}}~,
\end{equation}
where $N_d$ represents impurity concentration in conducting channel, $\mu_{min}$ and $\mu_{max}$ are the minimum and maximum mobilities, respectively. $N_r$ and $\alpha$ represent empirical constants. A plot of Eq. \eqref{Eq:1.2} as a function of $N_d$ for 4H-SiC is shown in Fig. \ref{Fig:1.1}. This is a typical Fermi-Dirac distribution profile where $\mu_0$ is reducing at higher values of $N_d$ due to increased ionized impurity scattering.

At elevated temperature, the amplitude of lattice vibration increases, causing more obstruction to the flow of carriers thus, reducing $\mu_0$. This requires modification in Eq. \ref{Eq:1.2}, which leads to a temperature dependent $\mu_{0}$ defined as \cite{Hjelmgren2007}
\begin{equation}
\label{Eq:1.3}
\mu_{0}(N_d,T) = \mu_{min}\left(\frac{T}{300}\right)^{-\beta} + \frac{\left(\mu_{max}-\mu_{min}\right)\left(T/300\right)^{-\beta}}{1+\left(N_d/N_{r}\right)^{\alpha}}~,
\end{equation}
where $T$ represents temperature in Kelvin and $\beta$ is a fitting variable whose value is defined in Table \ref{Table 1.3} \cite{Hjelmgren2007}. Eq. \ref{Eq:1.3} shows reduction in mobility by increasing the temperature whose value can be controlled by $\beta$ at a given temperature.

\begin{figure}
\centering
%\includegraphics [scale=0.5]{3D}
\includegraphics [width=4.5in, height=4in]{ThesisFigs/Fig1_1.pdf}
\caption{Mobility as a function of donor impurities.}
\label{Fig:1.1}
\end{figure}

For a given device, the value of $\mu$ is also dependent on the applied electric field, $E$, which is given by \cite{Caughey1967}
\begin{equation}
\label{Eq:1.4}
\mu(E) = \frac{\mu(N_d,T)}{\left\{1+\left[\mu(N_d,T)E/\upsilon_{s}\right]^p\right\}^{1/p}}~,
\end{equation}
where $p$ is an empirical constant. Relationship between $\mu$ and $\upsilon$ of a device is governed by the expression
\begin{equation}
\label{Eq:1.5}
\upsilon\left(E\right)=\mu\left(E\right) \times E~.
\end{equation}
By assuming the values given in Table \ref{Table 1.3}, variation in $\upsilon$ as a function of $E$ at different temperatures is shown in Fig. \ref{Fig:1.2}. The plot exhibits that pre-saturation $\upsilon$ shows strong dependence on temperature and it decreases with increasing temperature values. This reduction in $\upsilon$ is primarily associated with the reduction in $\mu$ at elevated temperature due to increased lattice scattering $\sim$1$\times$10$^6$ V/cm. Further, it is also evident from Fig. \ref{Fig:1.2} that $\upsilon$ saturates at $E$ commonly known as saturation field, $E_{s}$. Majority of figure-of-merits of SiC are based on carrier's mobility and velocity detail of which are given in the next section.

