\section{Figure of Merit}

There are several criteria (Figure of Merits) to compare the performance of semiconductor materials and devices, for high frequency and high power applications. Johnson suggested a figure of merit (JFOM), which considers the potential of power handling and high frequency capability of a device. JFOM takes into account $E_{crit}$ and $\upsilon_{s}$, as given in the following equation \cite{Johnson1966}:
\begin{equation}
\label{Eq:1.6}
\text{JFOM}=\dfrac{E^{2}_{crit}\upsilon^{2}_{s}}{4\pi^{2}}~.
\end{equation}
JFOM does not take into account the material's thermal properties, which are critically important at high power operation, so, Keyes \cite{Keyes1972} proposed another figure of merit (KFOM), which provides thermal limitation to the switching behavior of transistors used in integrated circuits.
\begin{equation}
\label{Eq:1.7}
\text{KFOM}=\kappa\sqrt{\dfrac{c\upsilon_{s}}{4\pi\varepsilon_s}}~,
\end{equation}
where $c$ represents speed of light in vacuum. Neither JFOM nor KFOM gives any information about power handling capabilities of a device and consequently, Baliga proposed another figure of merit (BFOM) \cite{Baliga1989}, which involves material parameters to address conduction losses.
\begin{equation}
\label{Eq:1.8}
\text{BFOM}=\varepsilon_s\mu_0 E^{3}_{g}~,
\end{equation}
where $E_{g}$ is the bandgap of a semiconductor.

Table \ref{Table 1.4} presents a summary of figure-of-merits of SiC relative to Si. It shows that SiC power devices have greater potential in performance over Si and GaAs power devices.

